<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-22T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-22T07:00:00-05:00" n="778" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d778">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.01/663: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-22T14:00:00+02:00">October
                                    22, 1942—2 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received October 22—12:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>406. With reference to my telegram 307 of August 25, noon and despatch
                            No. 457 of same date,<note n="31" xml:id="d778fn31">Latter not
                                printed.</note> I have received a note from the Lebanese Minister
                            for Foreign Affairs stating that the Council of Ministers at its meeting
                            of October 7, 1942 decided to exonerate the American philanthropic,
                            educational and religious institutions from all municipal and customs
                            taxes in conformity with the treaties and conventions in force.</p>
                        <p>The tenor of this note is very similar to that of the Syrian decree
                            reported in my 340, September 12, 9 a.m. and would appear scarcely to
                            satisfy the request contained in the informal <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> I left with the Lebanese Minister.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gwynn</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>